9. Describe a flow you have built end-to-end? Have you used approval flows? How did you implement them?

EXPLAIN IN ANSWER:-
â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”
âœ… Yes, I have built several approval flows using Power Automate â€” here's one real-time example:

"In my project, I implemented an approval flow using Power Automate integrated with Dataverse and Power Apps. 
First, I created a Dataverse table to store purchase order details such as employee name, order information, manager, and status. 
Then I created an automated cloud flow with the trigger 'When a row is added' in Dataverse.
Whenever a new order was created from Power Apps, the flow was triggered automatically. 
After that, I used the 'Get user profile (V2)' action to fetch the managerâ€™s email dynamically.
I used the 'Start and wait for an approval' action to send the approval request to the manager with all the order details.
Once the manager approved or rejected the request, 
I add "Update item "action for SP & Dataverse .
I used a condition to check the outcome and updated the status in the Dataverse table accordingly. 
I also sent email notifications to the employee informing them about the approval or rejection.

# 5 Types of Approvals:
1. Approve/Reject â€“ First to respond
2. Approve/Reject â€“ Everyone must approve
3. Custom Responses â€“ Wait for one response
4. Custom Responses â€“ Wait for all responses

âœ… How to send an Reminder emails using approvals:

"To achieve reminder emails for pending approvals, I implement it using Power Automate with parallel branch and delay functionality. 
After the 'Start and wait for an approval' action, 
I add a parallel branch. 
In one branch, the flow waits for the approval response, and in the other branch, I use a 'Delay' action for 3 days.

After the delay, I add a condition to check the approval status. 
If the approval is still pending, I send a reminder email to the manager using the 'Send an email (V2)' action. 
If the approval is already completed, the reminder email is not sent.
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

10. What is Concurrency Control in Power Automate?

EXPLAIN IN ANSWER:-
â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”
ğŸ‘‰ Concurrency Control helps you manage how many simultaneous (parallel) flow runs can happen at the same time. 
   â€” especially important when working with loops (Apply to each).

ğŸ”¹ Why It's Needed:
ğŸ‘‰ When a loop processes many items (e.g., SharePoint list items, array values), Power Automate runs iterations in parallel by default.
ğŸ”¹ This can:
ğŸ‘‰ Improve performance âœ…
ğŸ‘‰ But also cause data conflicts, race conditions âŒ (e.g., when updating same record or sending multiple dependent actions)

ğŸ”§ How to Enable/Disable:
ğŸ‘‰ In your flow, go to "Apply to each" â†’ Click ellipsis (...)
ğŸ‘‰ Choose "Settings"
ğŸ‘‰ You'll see a setting:
ğŸ”˜ Concurrency Control â†’ Turn it On
ğŸ‘‰ Set Degree of Parallelism (e.g., 1 to 50)





